@SimuLord So before I respond, I just wanted to say thanks for highlighting your story. I 100% agree that it is possible (and many people do) work their way back from street homelessness. My areas of research work in public health are homelessness, substance use, and health behavior, and I've interviewed research participants with similar stories. 

But you're right, I suspect we do disagree on solutions. Though I don't necessarily disagree that poverty (and the intersections that poverty has with subsistence living, crime, and substance use) generates a state of mind and way of social interaction that makes escaping difficult. I also don't disagree that among the "less fortunate" there are some pretty, let's say not-so-good people. But those people exist at every income level and in every demographic, they just aren't scrutinized the same way that people living in poverty are. At least from my own experience working in the community for about a decade now, conversing with community members and people who work with them, and the literature; I see the causality the other way around. Socio-structural factors perpetuate poverty, which drives both health outcomes and as you put it the "culture". I don't see it as possible to fix a downstream problem before an upstream one. I agree that the social services landscape has a wild number of problems, mainly being so overly bureaucratic that navigating them is next to impossible. 

It's the same reason that criminalization of drug use doesn't hasn't solved the drug overdose or Hep C crises. If there isn't work done to address the reasons so many people fall into substance use disorders (trauma, poverty, social neglect), the end results won't change much.

